column36: image
column162: I tended to use their stances on social and economic issues and experience to make a decision on their capabilities on being a government official before anything else, most other factors did a small part in swaying my decision. I tried to not take the election personally, but chose based on how I think they would run the country compared to my ideals. As an atheist I would prefer someone in office who is not religious but if they are and all other factors tell me they will do their job, I will vote for them. I used their party somewhat to make a decision based on what they would actually try to do with government when I paired it with their stances on issues, but not a factor itself in swaying my decision. Polling was only an enforcer for my decision to back up someone already doing good but not actually a decision making factor. Religion only played a part when candidates incorporated their beliefs into government, such as creation theory being taught in school, I highly disliked that and it did play a part in me not liking a candidate. I liked when a candidate believed in and backed up scientific research such as that in the stem cell field. I did not like either candidate in the last(third) election but I would have preferred the Democratic candidate(on the right) over the other by a small margin (in case I got the names mixed up). On the second election I did forget the names of the candidates and randomly voted, but I wanted to vote for the Republican candidate and treated the person I voted for randomly as that candidate.

I used their party somewhat to make a decision based on what they would actually try to do with government when I paired it with their stances on issues, but not a factor itself in swaying my decision. Polling was only an enforcer for my decision to back up someone already doing good but not actually a decision making factor. Religion only played a part when candidates incorporated their beliefs into government, such as creation theory being taught in school, I highly disliked that and it did play a part in me not liking a candidate. I liked when a candidate believed in and backed up scientific research such as that in the stem cell field. I did not like either candidate in the last(third) election but I would have preferred the Democratic candidate(on the right) over the other by a small margin (in case I got the names mixed up). On the second election I did forget the names of the candidates and randomly voted, but I wanted to vote for the Republican candidate and treated the person I voted for randomly as that candidate.
